\section*{Key Terms}
\nopagebreak[4]
\begin{samepage}
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Path Loss:} Path loss refers to the reduction in power density of an electromagnetic wave as it propagates through space. It is typically expressed in decibels (dB) and calculated using the Friis transmission formula. Notation: \(PL = 10 \log_{10} \left(\frac{P_t}{P_r}\right)\)

  \item \textbf{Fading:} Fading describes the variation in the amplitude of a signal received by an antenna due to changes in the transmission medium or path. Types include multipath and shadow fading. Notation: \(F_d\)

  \item \textbf{Friis Transmission Equation:} The Friis Transmission Equation is used to calculate the power received by an antenna from another antenna that is some distance away, assuming line-of-sight propagation. Notation: \(P_r = P_t + G_t + G_r - L_p\)

  \item \textbf{Multipath:} Multipath refers to the propagation phenomenon where signal waves reflect off objects and arrive at the receiver at different times, causing interference. Notation: \(M_p\)
\end{itemize}
\end{samepage}

\section*{Theory Sections}
\nopagebreak[4]
\begin{samepage}
\subsection*{Introduction to Wireless Propagation}
Wireless propagation involves the transmission of electromagnetic waves from a transmitter to a receiver over the air. This process is fundamental to all wireless communication systems and is influenced by various factors including the frequency of operation, the environment, and the antenna characteristics. Understanding the mechanisms of wireless propagation helps in designing more efficient and reliable communication systems. The path loss is a critical concept in wireless propagation. It quantifies the reduction in power density of the electromagnetic wave as it propagates through space. The path loss increases with the distance between the transmitter and the receiver and is also affected by the medium through which the wave travels. In free space, path loss can be calculated using the Friis transmission formula, which is derived from the inverse square law of distance and the gain of the antennas involved. Another important aspect of wireless propagation is fading. Fading is the variation in the amplitude and phase of a signal at a receiver due to changes in the transmission path. Common types of fading include multipath fading, where signals take multiple paths to reach the receiver, and Doppler fading, which is caused by relative motion between the transmitter and the receiver. This section will delve deeper into these concepts, providing a foundation for understanding more complex interactions in RF communication systems.

\textbf{Key Points:}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Path loss is critical in understanding signal attenuation over distance.
  \item Fading significantly affects the reliability of wireless channels.
  \item The Friis transmission equation models free space path loss.
\end{itemize}
\end{samepage}

