\section*{Key Terms}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Microcontroller:} A compact integrated circuit designed to govern a specific operation in an embedded system.
    \item \textbf{Arduino:} An open-source platform used for building electronics projects that include a programmable circuit board.
    \item \textbf{Sketch:} The name used for a program written on the Arduino IDE to communicate with the Arduino hardware.
    \item \textbf{PWM (Pulse Width Modulation):} A technique used to control analog circuits with a digital output from a microcontroller.
    \item \textbf{GPIO (General Purpose Input/Output):} Pins on a microcontroller that can be used for both input and output functions.
    \item \textbf{IDE (Integrated Development Environment):} A software application that provides programming facilities to developers, including code editing and debugging.
    \item \textbf{Analog Read:} A method that reads the value from a specified analog pin and returns it between 0 and 1023.
    \item \textbf{Digital Write:} A command to set a digital pin to a high or low voltage.
    \item \textbf{Serial Communication:} A process that allows Arduino to communicate with computers and other devices through a serial interface.
    \item \textbf{Library:} A collection of precompiled routines that a program can use, including commands to handle sensors or communications.
\end{itemize}

\section*{Theory Sections}

\subsection*{Introduction to Arduino Platform}
Arduino is an open-source electronics platform based on easy-to-use hardware and software. It's intended for anyone making interactive projects. Arduino boards are able to read inputs from a variety of sources, such as a light on a sensor, a finger on a button, or a Twitter message, and turn it into an output - activating a motor, turning on an LED, publishing something online, etc. You can tell your board what to do by sending a set of instructions to the microcontroller on the board. To do so, you use the Arduino programming language (based on Wiring), and the Arduino Software (IDE), based on Processing. The platform has grown through the years based on feedback and contributions from users around the world.

\subsection*{Arduino Board Components}
Each Arduino board consists of a set of digital and analog input/output (I/O) pins that can interface with various expansion boards and other circuits. The boards feature serial communication interfaces, including Universal Serial Bus (USB) on some models, for loading programs from personal computers. The microcontrollers are typically programmed using either the Arduino integrated development environment (IDE) or a web-based IDE. A feature of the Arduino is its availability, as almost anyone can purchase and use it while being professionally manufactured and having extensive community support worldwide.

\subsection*{Setting Up the Arduino IDE}
To start coding on an Arduino, you'll first have to set up the Arduino IDE on your computer. The IDE is where you'll write and upload code to the Arduino board. Begin by downloading the IDE from the official Arduino website. Follow the installation instructions specific to your operating system (Windows, macOS, Linux). Once installed, connect your Arduino board via the USB cable and open the Arduino IDE. Set the board type and port by navigating to the settings in the IDE. You are now ready to begin writing your sketches, which is Arduino's term for your program code.

\subsection*{Programming the Arduino: Basic Syntax and Structures}
The Arduino programming language is a set of C/C++ functions. Knowing basic syntax and structures will aid in effective programming. The main structures include \texttt{setup()} and \texttt{loop()} functions. The \texttt{setup()} function runs once at the start of a program, typically to initialize settings, while the \texttt{loop()} function repeats continuously, allowing the board to react instantly to inputs and outputs. Common programming commands include \texttt{pinMode()} for pin configuration, \texttt{digitalWrite()} for output control, and \texttt{digitalRead()} for input monitoring. Libraries can be included to expand the functionality of the Arduino, such as servo motor control or LED matrix management.

\subsection*{Debugging and Troubleshooting Arduino Projects}
Troubleshooting is an essential skill when working with Arduino projects. Start by checking simple issues such as loose connections or incorrect pin configurations. The Serial Monitor in Arduino IDE can be an invaluable tool to diagnose problems by displaying print statements from the board. Check for software issues, like incorrect syntax or incompatible libraries. Finally, review power supply items since inadequate power can lead to erratic behavior. By following a systematic debugging process, most issues can be resolved, leading to smooth-running projects.

\section*{Worked Examples}

\subsection*{Blinking LED}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Problem Statement:} Create a program to make an LED blink.
    \item \textbf{Solution Steps:}
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item Connect an LED to digital pin 13 on the Arduino.
        \item Open the Arduino IDE, create a new sketch.
        \item Use the \texttt{pinMode(13, OUTPUT);} function in the setup() to initialize the pin as an output.
        \item Write \texttt{digitalWrite(13, HIGH);} in the loop() function to turn on the LED.
        \item Include \texttt{delay(1000);} to keep the LED on for a second.
        \item Follow with \texttt{digitalWrite(13, LOW);} to turn off the LED.
        \item Add another \texttt{delay(1000);} to create a blink effect every second.
    \end{enumerate}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Reading a Potentiometer}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Problem Statement:} Read the value from a potentiometer and output it.
    \item \textbf{Solution Steps:}
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item Connect a potentiometer to analog pin A0 on the Arduino.
        \item In a new sketch, use \texttt{int sensorValue;} to store the potentiometer value.
        \item In setup(), initialize the serial communication with \texttt{Serial.begin(9600);}.
        \item In the loop(), read the value using \texttt{sensorValue = analogRead(A0);}.
        \item Print the value using \texttt{Serial.println(sensorValue);} to the Serial Monitor.
        \item Use \texttt{delay(100);} to update the reading every 100 milliseconds.
    \end{enumerate}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Servo Motor Control}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Problem Statement:} Control a servo motor using Arduino.
    \item \textbf{Solution Steps:}
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item Connect the servo motor to pin 9 on the Arduino.
        \item Include the Servo library at the top of your sketch with \texttt{\#include <Servo.h>}.
        \item Create a Servo object using \texttt{Servo myservo;}.
        \item In setup(), attach the servo to pin 9 using \texttt{myservo.attach(9);}.
        \item In the loop(), use \texttt{myservo.write(0);} to set the position at 0 degrees.
        \item Add \texttt{delay(1000);} to maintain this position for a second.
        \item Move the servo with \texttt{myservo.write(180);} to 180 degrees.
        \item Use another \texttt{delay(1000);} to keep this position for a second.
    \end{enumerate}
\end{itemize}

