\section*{Key Terms}
\begin{description}
    \item[Analog Signal:] An analog signal is a continuously variable signal that represents physical measurements. It is used in electronics to denote varying voltage levels which correspond to different physical phenomena.
    \item[ADC (Analog to Digital Converter):] An ADC is a system that converts an analog signal into a digital format. In Arduino, the ADC reads varying voltage levels and outputs digital values that can be used for processing.
    \item[Resolution:] Resolution refers to the smallest change a system can detect. A 10-bit ADC on an Arduino implies 1024 possible digital values (0 to 1023) representing the input voltage range.
    \item[Voltage Reference:] Voltage reference is a defined voltage level used by the ADC for comparison to determine input voltages. It can be internal or external, with common defaults of 5V or 3.3V on Arduino boards.
    \item[Pin Configuration:] Pin configuration details the specific pins used for analog inputs and their setup requirements. Different Arduino models support varying numbers of analog pins.
    \item[Sampling Rate:] Sampling rate is the frequency at which an analog signal is sampled by the ADC. A higher sampling rate allows for finer temporal resolution of the signal.
    \item[Noise:] Noise consists of any unwanted electrical signals that distort the desired signal, potentially affecting measurement accuracy and precision.
    \item[Signal Conditioning:] Signal conditioning involves techniques used to convert an analog input into a suitable form for accurate and reliable ADC conversion.
    \item[Latency:] Latency refers to the delay between an analog input signal being received and its digital representation being available for processing.
    \item[Decoupling Capacitor:] A decoupling capacitor is used in circuits to improve voltage stability and reduce noise, often placed near the power and ground pins of a circuit component.
    \item[Averaging Filter:] An averaging filter smoothes a signal by averaging successive samples, reducing noise and enhancing the stability of readings.
    \item[Sensor Interfacing:] Sensor interfacing involves connecting and configuring sensors to read data accurately via analog inputs, requiring attention to wiring and environmental factors.
\end{description}

