\section{Key Terms}
\subsection{Timer Interrupts}
Timer interrupts are signals emitted by hardware timers in microcontrollers to manage the execution of specific tasks at set intervals. They are critical in real-time systems for precise timing operations. Notation: $\text{Interrupt}$.

\subsection{Duty Cycle}
The duty cycle is the fraction of one period in which a signal or system is active. It is a key parameter in pulse-width modulation (PWM) used in controlling power delivery. Notation: $\text{DutyCycle} = \frac{\text{ActiveTime}}{\text{TotalPeriod}}$.

\subsection{Proximity Sensors}
Devices that detect the presence or absence of an object within a defined range using various technologies like infrared, ultrasonic, or capacitive sensors. Notation: $\text{Sensor}$.

\subsection{Latency}
The time delay between the initiation of a process and its execution, crucial in systems where real-time processing is required. Minimizing latency is essential for the efficient performance of proximity monitoring systems. Notation: $\text{Latency}$.

\subsection{Real-Time Operating System (RTOS)}
An operating system designed to manage hardware resources and run applications with precise timing and high reliability, necessary for deploying real-time embedded systems. Notation: $\text{RTOS}$.

\subsection{Feedback Loop}
A system structure where the output is fed back into the input to maintain a desired state, often used in control systems to ensure stability and accuracy. Notation: $\text{FeedbackLoop}$.

\section{Theory}
\subsection{Introduction to Timer-Based Systems}
The use of timers in embedded systems is fundamental for applications requiring precise timekeeping and control. Timers can be hardware-based, integrated into microcontrollers, or software-based, relying on program execution timing. They serve multiple purposes, such as generating time delays, measuring intervals, and triggering events. The key to leveraging timers effectively lies in understanding their configuration and the role of interrupts in maintaining system responsiveness. In real-time systems, timers are essential for managing processes like task scheduling, input/output operations, and communication protocols. By employing timers, systems can operate autonomously and react to changes instantly without continuous CPU intervention. The mathematical modeling of timer operations involves calculations of frequency, period, and duty cycle, which are crucial for designing systems that meet specific timing requirements. For instance, in a timer with a frequency of $f = \frac{1}{T}$, where $T$ is the period, the configuration of the timer registers will determine the behavior of the system under various conditions.

