\subsection{Proximity Monitoring Techniques}
Proximity monitoring systems utilize sensors to detect the presence or absence of objects within a defined range. These systems can employ various sensing technologies, including infrared, ultrasonic, and capacitive sensing. Each method has its advantages and limitations; for example, infrared sensors offer simplicity and low cost but may be affected by environmental conditions, while ultrasonic sensors provide accuracy over longer distances. The design of a proximity monitoring system involves selecting the appropriate sensor technology and integrating it with a timer-based control mechanism to ensure timely response and efficient power management. The use of pulse-width modulation (PWM) and duty cycle adjustments allows for dynamic control of sensor operation, optimizing performance while conserving energy. The integration of these systems into a broader control loop can enhance capabilities such as object tracking and collision avoidance, which are vital in industrial automation and robotics.

