\section{Worked Examples}
\subsection{Basic Edge-triggered Interrupt (Difficulty: Basic)}
\textbf{Problem:} Describe how an edge-triggered interrupt can be implemented in an Arduino to detect a button press.

\textbf{Given:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Arduino Uno board
    \item Push button connected to digital pin 2
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Required:} Implement the ISR and main loop code.

\textbf{Solution:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Initialize the pin mode for the button.
    \begin{equation}
    \text{pinMode(2, INPUT);}
    \end{equation}
    \item Attach the interrupt to the button pin.
    \begin{equation}
    \text{attachInterrupt(digitalPinToInterrupt(2), buttonPressISR, RISING);}
    \end{equation}
    \item Define the ISR function to handle the button press.
    \begin{equation}
    \text{void buttonPressISR() \{ buttonPressed = true; \}}
    \end{equation}
    \item In the main loop, check if the button was pressed.
    \begin{equation}
    \text{if (buttonPressed) \{ // handle press; buttonPressed = false; \}}
    \end{equation}
    \item Reset the button state after handling.
    \begin{equation}
    \text{buttonPressed = false;}
    \end{equation}
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Answer:} \boxed{\text{Implemented ISR and main loop for edge-triggered button detection.}}

\textbf{Teaching Notes:} Emphasize the importance of debouncing in real applications.

\textbf{Common Mistakes:}
