\section{Key Terms}
\subsection{Interrupt}
An interrupt is a signal emitted by hardware or software indicating an event that needs immediate attention, allowing the CPU to halt its current operations to address the event. Interrupts are crucial for managing asynchronous events in embedded systems. They enable efficient CPU utilization by allowing the processor to respond to high-priority tasks without polling. Notation: $\text{INT}$.

\subsection{Interrupt Service Routine (ISR)}
An ISR is a special block of code associated with a specific interrupt that executes in response to an interrupt signal, handling the event and returning control back to the main program flow. ISRs must be efficient and concise to minimize system latency. Notation: $\text{ISR}$.

\subsection{Nested Interrupts}
Nested interrupts refer to the ability of a system to handle multiple interrupt signals simultaneously, allowing higher priority interrupts to preempt lower priority ones. This feature is essential for real-time systems requiring quick responses to critical events. Notation: $\text{NIV}$.

\subsection{Interrupt Vector Table}
The interrupt vector table is a data structure that holds the addresses of ISRs, allowing the CPU to quickly locate and execute the appropriate ISR when an interrupt occurs. It is a crucial component for efficient interrupt management. Notation: $\text{IVT}$.

\subsection{Latency}
Latency in interrupt handling refers to the time delay from the generation of an interrupt to the start of its associated ISR, affecting the system's responsiveness. Minimizing latency is critical for real-time performance. Notation: $\text{LAT}$.

\section{Theory}
\subsection{Introduction to Interrupts}
Interrupts are fundamental to modern embedded systems, providing a mechanism for the CPU to respond to asynchronous events. An interrupt allows the processor to pause its current execution to address a more immediate task, enhancing the responsiveness and efficiency of the system. The interrupt vector table plays a crucial role, mapping interrupts to their corresponding ISRs, ensuring that each event is handled appropriately. Understanding how interrupts work, their types, and how they are managed is essential for designing robust embedded applications.

Key Points:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Definition and purpose of interrupts
    \item Role of the interrupt vector table
    \item Types of interrupts (hardware vs. software)
\end{itemize}

Related Outcomes: LO1

\subsection{Designing Interrupt Service Routines (ISRs)}
ISRs serve as the heart of interrupt handling, executing specific tasks when an interrupt is triggered. A well-designed ISR should be concise, efficient, and capable of handling the event with minimal delay. Key considerations include minimizing latency, prioritizing critical tasks, and ensuring proper context switching. The use of ISRs varies based on system requirements, from simple flag setting to complex data processing, making their design a critical aspect of embedded system development.

Key Points:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Characteristics of effective ISRs
    \item Context switching and latency considerations
    \item Examples of ISR applications
\end{itemize}

Related Outcomes: LO2

\subsection{Nested Interrupts and Prioritization}
Nested interrupts enable a system to manage multiple interrupt requests efficiently by allowing higher priority interrupts to preempt lower ones. This capability is crucial in systems where timely response to critical events is paramount. Designing a system with nested interrupts involves configuring interrupt priorities, understanding the trade-offs between responsiveness and complexity, and ensuring that ISRs are reentrant if necessary. Mastering nested interrupts is key to developing real-time systems with multiple concurrent tasks.

Key Points:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Concept and advantages of nested interrupts
    \item Configuring interrupt priorities
    \item Challenges and solutions in nested interrupt systems
\end{itemize}

Related Outcomes: LO3

\subsection{Analyzing System Performance with Interrupts}
The performance of an embedded system heavily relies on how efficiently it handles interrupts. Analyzing interrupt latency, throughput, and overall system load provides insights into system performance and areas for optimization. Techniques such as measuring ISR execution time, evaluating context switch overhead, and using profiling tools are essential for identifying bottlenecks and improving system efficiency. Understanding these performance metrics allows engineers to design systems that meet stringent real-time requirements.

Key Points:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Importance of analyzing interrupt performance
    \item Tools and techniques for performance measurement
    \item Strategies for optimizing interrupt handling
\end{itemize}

Related Outcomes: LO4

