\section*{Key Terms}
\subsection*{Antiderivative}
An antiderivative of a function $f(x)$ is a function $F(x)$ such that $F'(x) = f(x)$.

\subsection*{Indefinite Integral}
The indefinite integral of a function is the set of all its antiderivatives, denoted by $\int f(x) \, dx$.

\subsection*{Integration Constant}
The constant $C$ added to an antiderivative to account for all possible solutions.

\subsection*{Power Rule for Integration}
If $n \neq -1$, then $\int x^n \, dx = \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1} + C$.

\subsection*{Initial Condition}
A given value that allows determination of the integration constant $C$.

\subsection*{Area Under Curve}
The area under a curve $f(x)$ from $a$ to $b$ is given by the definite integral $\int_a^b f(x) \, dx$.

\section*{Theory}
\subsection*{Understanding Antiderivatives}
An antiderivative of a function $f(x)$ is a function $F(x)$ such that $F'(x) = f(x)$. The process of finding an antiderivative is called antidifferentiation or integration. Unlike differentiation, integration has no unique solution; it includes an arbitrary constant $C$.
\[
\int f(x) \, dx = F(x) + C
\]

\subsection*{Basic Integration Techniques}
Basic integration involves finding the indefinite integral of a function using known rules. The most common rule is the power rule: If $n \neq -1$, then $\int x^n \, dx = \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1} + C$. This rule helps integrate polynomials easily.
\[
\int x^n \, dx = \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1} + C
\]

\subsection*{Integration and Areas}
Integration can be used to find the area under a curve defined by a function over a certain interval. The definite integral is defined as the limit of a sum of areas of rectangles, providing a way to calculate areas precisely.
\[
\int_a^b f(x) \, dx
\]

\subsection*{Constants of Integration}
When finding antiderivatives, it is crucial to include the constant of integration $C$. This constant accounts for the family of functions that differ by a constant, all of which have the same derivative.
\[
F(x) = \int f(x) \, dx + C
\]

