\section*{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}\nopagebreak[4]

Differentiation and integration of logarithmic and exponential functions form a cornerstone of calculus, providing essential tools for analyzing growth processes, decay phenomena, and complex relationships in mathematical modeling. These functions are ubiquitous in fields ranging from engineering and physics to economics and biology. Understanding how to manipulate these functions through differentiation and integration is crucial for solving real-world problems. This chapter will delve into the techniques for differentiating and integrating these functions, building on foundational calculus concepts.

In previous lessons, you explored the basics of differentiation and integration, focusing on polynomial functions. This lesson extends those principles to logarithmic and exponential functions, which exhibit unique properties and require specific techniques. By mastering these methods, you will enhance your ability to model and solve complex problems involving exponential growth and decay, such as population dynamics, radioactive decay, and financial forecasting.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Theory of Differentiation and Integration}\label{sec:theory}\nopagebreak[4]

The differentiation and integration of logarithmic and exponential functions are pivotal in calculus due to their extensive applications in various scientific fields. The exponential function, denoted as \( e^x \), is unique because its derivative is itself, \( \frac{d}{dx} e^x = e^x \). This property makes exponential functions particularly useful in modeling natural growth processes and decay.

Logarithmic functions, such as \( \ln(x) \), are the inverse of exponential functions. The derivative of the natural logarithm function is \( \frac{d}{dx} \ln(x) = \frac{1}{x} \), which is derived from the chain rule. This derivative is fundamental in simplifying complex expressions involving logarithms.

Integration, the inverse process of differentiation, involves finding the antiderivative of a function. For exponential functions, the integral \( \int e^x \, dx = e^x + C \) is straightforward due to the self-replicating nature of the exponential function. For logarithmic functions, integration often requires techniques such as integration by parts, especially when dealing with products of logarithmic and polynomial functions.

