\caption{Graph of the exponential function \(e^x\) and the logarithmic function \(\ln(x)\).}
\end{figure}

The product rule and chain rule are essential tools for differentiating functions involving products or compositions of logarithmic and exponential functions. The product rule states that the derivative of a product of two functions \( u(x) \) and \( v(x) \) is given by \( (uv)' = u'v + uv' \). The chain rule is used when differentiating a composite function \( f(g(x)) \), and is expressed as \( \frac{d}{dx} f(g(x)) = f'(g(x))g'(x) \).

