\begin{solutionbox}
\textbf{Exercise 1: Differentiate \( f(x) = x^3 \ln(x) \)}\\[0.5em]
\textbf{Step 1: Apply the Product Rule}\\
The product rule states that \((uv)' = u'v + uv'\).
\begin{align*}
u &= x^3, & v &= \ln(x) \\
u' &= 3x^2, & v' &= \frac{1}{x}
\end{align*}
\textbf{Step 2: Substitute into the Product Rule}\\
\begin{align*}
f'(x) &= 3x^2 \ln(x) + x^3 \cdot \frac{1}{x} \\
      &= 3x^2 \ln(x) + x^2
\end{align*}
\[\boxed{f'(x) = 3x^2 \ln(x) + x^2}\]
\end{solutionbox}
\end{samepage}

