\section{Inverse Hyperbolic Functions}\label{sec:invhyper}\nopagebreak[4]
Inverse hyperbolic functions are analogous to inverse trigonometric functions but relate to hyperbolic functions such as hyperbolic sine, cosine, and tangent. These functions are essential in various scientific fields, including physics and engineering, due to their applications in modeling hyperbolic geometry and exponential growth processes.

The \textbf{inverse hyperbolic sine function}, \(\text{arsinh}(x)\), is defined as the inverse of the hyperbolic sine function, \(\sinh(x)\). It can be expressed as \(\text{arsinh}(x) = \ln(x + \sqrt{x^2 + 1})\). Similarly, the \textbf{inverse hyperbolic cosine function}, \(\text{arcosh}(x)\), is defined for \(x \geq 1\) and can be expressed as \(\text{arcosh}(x) = \ln(x + \sqrt{x^2 - 1})\). The \textbf{inverse hyperbolic tangent function}, \(\text{artanh}(x)\), is defined for \(|x| < 1\) and can be expressed as \(\text{artanh}(x) = \frac{1}{2}\ln\left(\frac{1+x}{1-x}\right)\).

These functions are useful in solving integrals involving hyperbolic functions. For example, the integral \(\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2 + 1}} \, dx\) evaluates to \(\text{arsinh}(x) + C\), where \(C\) is the constant of integration. Understanding the derivatives of these functions is also crucial, as they are often used in differential equations and other calculus applications. The derivative of \(\text{arsinh}(x)\) is \(\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2 + 1}}\), which is derived using the chain rule.

